{"timestamp":"2026-04-15T06:31:09.279Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"I checked `../../git`, and the main result is:\n\nThere is **no hidden stock protocol command** that says “give me the first-parent root” or “give me the kth ancestor of this commit”.\n\nThe useful pieces are:\n\n- `fetch` in protocol v2 supports `want`, `have`, `filter`, shallow/deepen, `packfile-uris`, etc., but no ancestry query in [gitprotocol-v2.adoc](../../git/Documentation/gitprotocol-v2.adoc).\n- `object-info` exists, but upstream Git only supports **object size**, not commit parents or commit metadata:\n  [gitprotocol-v2.adoc](../../git/Documentation/gitprotocol-v2.adoc:556)\n  [protocol-caps.c](../../git/protocol-caps.c:14)\n- `--negotiate-only` is only about finding commits you and the server already have in common, not arbitrary ancestors:\n  [fetch-options.adoc](../../git/Documentation/fetch-options.adoc:72)\n\nThe one trick that may actually matter is **shallow/deepen**.\n\nGit’s own docs and code show that `upload-pack` can compute shallow boundaries server-side:\n- `deepen-since` is internally like `rev-list --max-age=...`\n- `deepen-not` is internally like `rev-list --not <rev>`\n- the server replies with `shallow <oid>` boundary commits\n  [gitprotocol-capabilities.adoc](../../git/Documentation/gitprotocol-capabilities.adoc:220)\n  [upload-pack.c](../../git/upload-pack.c:908)\n  [gitprotocol-v2.adoc](../../git/Documentation/gitprotocol-v2.adoc:296)\n\nSo the interesting idea is:\n\n1. Request the branch tip with `deepen N` and `filter tree:0`.\n2. Let the server send only the top `N` generations of commit objects.\n3. Read the `shallow-info` response to get boundary commit IDs.\n4. Parse only that partial commit set in memory.\n5. Walk the first-parent chain within that partial slice.\n6. If the root is not in the slice, deepen again.\n\nWhy this is interesting:\n- It avoids fetching the **entire** commit graph up front.\n- It still works without